d sexual; the "multilingual reality" of the United States; the place of the Mexican-American War in U.S. history; and the significance of Tiger Woods in today's global market of consumption. Together, the essays propose a renewed vision of the United States' role in the world and how American Studies scholarship can address that vision. Each contributor includes a sample syllabus showing how the issues discussed in individual essays can be brought into the classroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCultural pluralismxStudy and teachingxUnited States. 0aCultural pluralismxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aNationalismxStudy and teachingxUnited States. 0aNationalismxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1990s.  aacademic.  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  aamerican studies.  acollege professor.  aessay anthology.  aessay collection.  aglobalism.  ahistorical.  ahistory professor.  ahistory teacher.  amigration.  anationalism.  anationalist.  anorth atlantic.  apost nationalist.  aprofessor.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  ascholarly.  asyllabi.  asyllabus.  ateacher.  aunited states history.  aunited states.  aus history.  awartime.1 aCuriel, Barbara Brinson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazanjian, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinney, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMailloux, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMechling, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowe, John Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowe, John Carlos, eeditor.4edt4